<div class="tribe-manual">
	<ManualHeader />

	<ManualPageNav @activePage="ai" />

	<div class="container pb-5">

		<div class="alert alert-dark mb-4">
			<h5 class="alert-heading mb-1">
				<i class="fa-solid fa-wand-sparkles me-2"></i>All README files in this
				ecosystem are optimised for AI
			</h5>
			<p class="mb-0 small">
				Every repository in the Tribe framework ships a README that has been
				written with AI consumption in mind — comprehensive API documentation,
				clear data models, code patterns and architectural explanations.
				Attaching the right README as context before asking an AI assistant to
				generate code dramatically improves the quality of the output.
			</p>
		</div>

		<div class="steps-container mb-5">

			<div
				class="step-card"
				data-step-name="Backend tribe-core README AI context PHP API"
			>
				<div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
					<span class="step-badge">1</span>
					<span class="step-title">Backend Projects — attach tribe-core's README</span>
					<i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
				</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<p>
						When working on anything backend — custom PHP endpoints,
						<code>pushObject</code>
						calls, API integrations, upload handling, or content type queries —
						start every AI session by attaching
						<strong>tribe-core's README</strong>
						as context.
					</p>
					<div class="row g-3">
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>What tribe-core's README covers</strong></h6>
									<ul class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
										<li>All
											<code>\Tribe\Core</code>
											methods:
											<code>pushObject</code>,
											<code>getObject</code>,
											<code>getIDs</code>,
											<code>deleteObject</code>,
											<code>pushObjects</code>
											(batch)</li>
										<li>Full JSON:API endpoint structure and request/response
											formats</li>
										<li>Authentication levels (public, API key, domain
											whitelisting)</li>
										<li>File upload response shapes including image size
											variants and HLS video</li>
										<li>Search parameters, range queries, pagination patterns</li>
										<li>Environment variable requirements</li>
									</ul>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>How to use it</strong></h6>
									<ol class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
										<li>Open the README at the link below</li>
										<li>Copy its full contents (or download the raw file)</li>
										<li>Paste it as the first message or attachment in your AI
											chat</li>
										<li>Then describe your task — the AI now has the full API
											contract</li>
									</ol>
									<div class="mt-3">
										<a
											href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tribe-framework/tribe-core/refs/heads/master/README.md"
											target="_blank"
											class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-dark"
											rel="noopener noreferrer"
										>
											<i class="fa-solid fa-file-lines me-1"></i>tribe-core
											README (raw)
										</a>
									</div>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div
				class="step-card"
				data-step-name="Frontend ember-tribe README AI context EmberJS"
			>
				<div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
					<span class="step-badge">2</span>
					<span class="step-title">Frontend Projects — attach ember-tribe's
						README</span>
					<i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
				</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<p>
						When building or extending a Tribe frontend — routes, components,
						services, forms, file upload UI, data querying — attach
						<strong>ember-tribe's README</strong>. It contains everything an AI
						needs to generate valid, idiomatic Tribe frontend code.
					</p>
					<div class="row g-3">
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>What ember-tribe's README covers</strong></h6>
									<ul class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
										<li>The 20+ mandatory code rules (EmberJS 6.x, Bootstrap 5,
											field access via
											<code>modules</code>, etc.)</li>
										<li>EmberData query patterns:
											<code>modules</code>
											(AND) vs
											<code>filter</code>
											(OR), pagination, sorting</li>
										<li>Route, controller, helper, modifier, service and
											component patterns with real examples</li>
										<li>Input field conventions:
											<code>&lt;Input&gt;</code>,
											<code>&lt;Textarea&gt;</code>,
											<code>ember-power-select</code></li>
										<li>File upload JavaScript pattern and the response shape</li>
										<li><code>storylang.json</code>
											spec format and how to use the CLI</li>
									</ul>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Ideal prompt structure</strong></h6>
									<p class="small text-muted mb-2">After attaching the README,
										structure your prompt like this:</p>
									<div class="bg-light p-2 rounded small font-monospace">
										[Paste ember-tribe README]<br /><br />
										Here is my types.json: [paste]<br />
										Here is my storylang.json: [paste]<br /><br />
										Build me a route that lists all [type] records, with
										pagination and search.
									</div>
									<div class="mt-3">
										<a
											href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tribe-framework/ember-tribe/refs/heads/master/README.md"
											target="_blank"
											class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-dark"
											rel="noopener noreferrer"
										>
											<i class="fa-solid fa-file-lines me-1"></i>ember-tribe
											README (raw)
										</a>
									</div>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div
				class="step-card"
				data-step-name="types.json blueprint AI context data architecture Junction"
			>
				<div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
					<span class="step-badge">3</span>
					<span class="step-title">Data Architecture — attach the types.json
						README</span>
					<i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
				</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<p>
						When designing a new data model, asking an AI to generate a
						<code>types.json</code>
						blueprint, or adding new tracks and modules to an existing project,
						attach the
						<strong>types.json repository README</strong>. It teaches the AI
						every valid field type, relationship pattern and Junction rule.
					</p>
					<div class="row g-3">
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>What types.json's README covers</strong></h6>
									<ul class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
										<li>Full field type reference: all HTML5 input types +
											Junction-specific (<code>editorjs</code>,
											<code>file_uploader</code>,
											<code>select</code>)</li>
										<li>Five
											<code>var_type</code>
											values and when to use each</li>
										<li>Relationship patterns using
											<code>linked_type</code></li>
										<li>Critical Junction rules:
											<code>sendable: false</code>, file uploader placement,
											reserved names</li>
										<li>SEO and Open Graph module conventions</li>
										<li>A complete worked example (news media blueprint)</li>
									</ul>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>How Junction AI deliverables work</strong></h6>
									<p class="small text-muted mb-2">
										When you describe your project in Junction's AI prompt, it
										returns a single JSON object with two keys:
									</p>
									<code class="small d-block bg-light p-2 rounded">
										{<br />
										&nbsp;&nbsp;"html": "consultation summary",<br />
										&nbsp;&nbsp;"json": "types.json blueprint"<br />
										}
									</code>
									<p class="small text-muted mt-2 mb-2">The
										<code>html</code>
										key contains a three-paragraph strategic consultation. The
										<code>json</code>
										key is the ready-to-use blueprint.</p>
									<a
										href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tribe-framework/types.json/refs/heads/master/README.md"
										target="_blank"
										class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-dark"
										rel="noopener noreferrer"
									>
										<i class="fa-solid fa-file-lines me-1"></i>types.json README
										(raw)
									</a>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div
				class="step-card"
				data-step-name="storylang.json AI spec full-stack frontend specification"
			>
				<div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
					<span class="step-badge">4</span>
					<span class="step-title">Use storylang.json as your AI Frontend Spec</span>
					<i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
				</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<p>
						<code>config/storylang.json</code>
						in your Ember app is not just a housekeeping file — it is the most
						precise description of what your frontend does that exists in the
						whole project. Attach it alongside
						<code>types.json</code>
						and the ember-tribe README for the most powerful AI frontend
						workflow.
					</p>
					<div class="row g-3">
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Why it's powerful for AI</strong></h6>
									<ul class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
										<li>Lists every route with its tracked vars, query params,
											actions and backend calls</li>
										<li>Maps exactly which types each route and component
											consumes</li>
										<li>Documents every service's internal methods, actions and
											dependencies</li>
										<li>Gives an AI the complete dependency graph of your
											frontend in a single JSON file</li>
										<li>Eliminates guesswork about naming conventions, file
											locations and patterns already in use</li>
									</ul>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="col-md-6">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Optimal full-stack prompt</strong></h6>
									<p class="small text-muted mb-2">For full-stack feature work,
										combine all three:</p>
									<ol class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
										<li>Attach
											<strong>ember-tribe README</strong>
											(code rules + patterns)</li>
										<li>Attach your
											<strong>types.json</strong>
											(data model)</li>
										<li>Attach your
											<strong>storylang.json</strong>
											(existing frontend structure)</li>
										<li>Describe the feature you want to add</li>
									</ol>
									<p class="small text-muted mt-2 mb-0">
										The AI will generate code that fits seamlessly into your
										existing architecture — correct field names, correct service
										names, correct patterns from day one.
									</p>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div
				class="step-card"
				data-step-name="Tribe README infrastructure Docker multi-tenant AI context"
			>
				<div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
					<span class="step-badge">5</span>
					<span class="step-title">Infrastructure Work — attach the Tribe &amp;
						Loom READMEs</span>
					<i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
				</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<p>
						For Docker configuration, environment setup, multi-tenant Loom
						provisioning, or Tor onion service configuration, the relevant
						README files give the AI exact service names, port conventions, env
						variable names and CLI commands.
					</p>
					<div class="row g-3">
						<div class="col-md-4">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Tribe (main)</strong></h6>
									<p class="small text-muted mb-2">Standard single-project
										setup, default ports, Docker CLI commands.</p>
									<a
										href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tribe-framework/tribe/refs/heads/master/README.md"
										target="_blank"
										class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-dark"
										rel="noopener noreferrer"
									>tribe README</a>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="col-md-4">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Loom (multi-tenant)</strong></h6>
									<p class="small text-muted mb-2">Thread isolation model,
										<code>loom.sh</code>
										CLI, port allocation, Typesense collection naming.</p>
									<a
										href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tribe-framework/tribe/refs/heads/master/config/loom/README.loom.md"
										target="_blank"
										class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-dark"
										rel="noopener noreferrer"
									>Loom README</a>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="col-md-4">
							<div class="card method-item h-100">
								<div class="card-body">
									<h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Tor (onion)</strong></h6>
									<p class="small text-muted mb-2">Hidden service setup, onion
										address generation, compose overlay structure.</p>
									<a
										href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tribe-framework/tribe/refs/heads/master/config/tor/README.tor.md"
										target="_blank"
										class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-dark"
										rel="noopener noreferrer"
									>Tor README</a>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div
				class="step-card"
				data-step-name="AI prompting quick reference cheat sheet tribe"
			>
				<div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
					<span class="step-badge">6</span>
					<span class="step-title">Quick Reference — What to attach for each
						task</span>
					<i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
				</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<p>Use this table as a quick reference when starting any AI-assisted
						task on a Tribe project:</p>
					<table class="table table-bordered table-sm small">
						<thead class="table-dark">
							<tr>
								<th>Task</th>
								<th>Primary context to attach</th>
								<th>Also attach</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							<tr>
								<td>Write a custom PHP endpoint or
									<code>pushObject</code>
									call</td>
								<td><code>tribe-core</code> README</td>
								<td>Your <code>types.json</code></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Build or extend an Ember route / component</td>
								<td><code>ember-tribe</code> README</td>
								<td>Your
									<code>types.json</code>
									+
									<code>storylang.json</code></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Design a new data model / generate
									<code>types.json</code></td>
								<td><code>types.json</code> README</td>
								<td>Your project description</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Add a new feature (full-stack)</td>
								<td><code>ember-tribe</code>
									README +
									<code>tribe-core</code>
									README</td>
								<td>Your
									<code>types.json</code>
									+
									<code>storylang.json</code></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Configure multi-tenant Loom setup</td>
								<td>Loom README</td>
								<td>Tribe main README</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Set up Tor / onion services</td>
								<td>Tor README</td>
								<td>Tribe main README</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Implement video upload &amp; playback</td>
								<td><code>tribe-core</code> README (Uploads class)</td>
								<td><code>ember-tribe</code>
									README (file upload pattern)</td>
							</tr>
						</tbody>
					</table>
					<div class="alert alert-success mt-2 mb-0 small">
						<strong>Pro tip:</strong>
						Run
						<code>node storylang</code>
						before starting any AI session on a frontend task. An up-to-date
						<code>storylang.json</code>
						gives the AI a live map of your entire frontend — no hallucinated
						file names or conflicting patterns.
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

		</div>

		<ManualFooter />

	</div>
</div>

<ManualScripts />
